<chapter id="configuring-your-system-chap" status="writing">
	<title id="configuring-your-system">Configuring Your System</title>
	<para>This chapter contains information on configuring your system.</para>
	<sect1 id="hardware" status="writing">
		<title>Hardware</title>
		<sect2 id="digital-cameras">
			<title>Digital Cameras</title>
				<para>Most USB digital cameras will be automatcially detected by Ubuntu. Simply just plug in and switch on your USB digital camera, Ubuntu will then ask you if you would like to import the photos from your camera. Click on <guibutton>Import</guibutton>, Ubuntu will then show you a preview of your photos. Choose a location to save your photos to, then click on <guibutton>Import</guibutton>, Ubuntu will then save your photos to your hard drive.</para>
		</sect2>
		<sect2 id="sound-cards">
			<title>Sound Cards</title>
				<para>Many common sound cards are automatically detected by Ubuntu during installation, if you are not hearing sound there are a couple of things you can try:</para>
		   <orderedlist>
			<listitem>
				<para>Check that the sound isn't muted, click the speaker icon on the top panel of your Ubuntu desktop and check each device.</para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
				<para>Check to see if root can use sound. Type into a terminal:</para>
		<para>
<screen>
sudo totem &amp;
</screen>
		</para>
		<para>Once <application>Totem</application> launches, try playing a sound or movie file. If the sound now works, do the following in a terminal to enable everyone to use sound:</para>
		<para>
<screen>
sudo chmod 666 /dev/dsp
</screen>
		</para>
			</listitem>
		    </orderedlist>
		<para>More information can be found on <ulink url="https://wiki.ubuntu.com/SoundProblemsHoary">SoundProblemsHoary</ulink> on the Ubuntu Wiki.</para>
		</sect2>

		<sect2 id="graphics-cards">
			<title>3D Graphic Cards</title>
		        <qandaset>
        	       	 <qandaentry id="installnvidiadriver" xreflabel="3D Nvidia video card driver">
        		        <question>
        		            <para>3D Nvidia Video Card Driver</para>
        		        </question>
        		        <answer>
        		            <orderedlist>
        		                <listitem>
        		                    <para>Read <xref linkend="extra-repositories"/></para>
        		                </listitem>
        		                <listitem>
				<para>Install the nvidia-glx and nvidia-settings packages with <application>Add/Remove Applications</application> (See <xref linkend="add-applications"/>)
				</para> 
                            <para>
                                <literallayout>Miscellaneous - Graphical (restricted) &gt; nvidia-glx
Miscellaneous - Graphical (restricted) &gt; nvidia-settings</literallayout>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>
                                <screen>
sudo cp /etc/X11/xorg.conf /etc/X11/xorg.conf_backup 
sudo nvidia-glx-config enable 
sudo gedit /usr/share/applications/NVIDIA-Settings.desktop</screen>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Insert the following lines into the new file
                                <programlisting>
[Desktop Entry]
Name=NVIDIA Settings
Comment=NVIDIA Settings
Exec=nvidia-settings
Icon=
Terminal=false
Type=Application
Categories=Application;System;</programlisting>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Save the edited file (<ulink
                                    url="sample/NVIDIA-Settings.desktop_installnvidiadriver"
                                />)</para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Read <xref linkend="restartgnomewithoutreboot"/>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>
                                <menuchoice>
                                    <guimenu>Applications</guimenu>
                                    <guisubmenu>System Tools</guisubmenu>
                                    <guimenuitem>NVIDIA Settings</guimenuitem>
                                </menuchoice>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                    </orderedlist>
                </answer>
            </qandaentry>
            <qandaentry>
                <question>
                    <para>Disable the Nvidia Graphics Logo on Startup</para>
                </question>
                <answer>
                    <orderedlist>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Read <xref linkend="installnvidiadriver"/>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>
                                <screen>
sudo cp /etc/X11/xorg.conf /etc/X11/xorg.conf_backup 
sudo gedit /etc/X11/xorg.conf</screen>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Find this section</para>
                            <para>
                                <programlisting>
...
Section "Device"
Identifier	"NVIDIA Corporation NV11 [GeForce2 MX/MX 400]"
Driver		"nvidia"
BusID		"PCI:1:0:0"
...</programlisting>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Add the following line below it</para>
                            <para>
                                <programlisting>
Option  "NoLogo"</programlisting>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Save the edited file ( <ulink
                                    url="sample/xorg.conf_disablenvidialogo"
                            />)</para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Read <xref linkend="restartgnomewithoutreboot"/>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
                    </orderedlist>
                </answer>
            </qandaentry>
	<!-- unconfirmed ATI drivers, someone who owns an ATI card please confirm that this works -->
            <qandaentry id="installatidriver">
                <question>
                    <para>3D ATI Video Card Driver</para>
                </question>
                <answer>
			<orderedlist>
                        <listitem>
 				<para>Install the xorg-driver-fglrx package with <application>Add/Remove Applications</application> (See <xref linkend="add-applications"/>)
				</para> 
                            <para>
                                <literallayout>Miscellaneous - Graphical (restricted) &gt; xorg-driver-fglrx</literallayout>
                            </para>
                        </listitem>
			<listitem>
			    <para><screen>
echo fglrx | sudo tee -a /etc/modules
sudo depmod -a ; sudo modprobe fglrx
sudo cp /etc/X11/xorg.conf /etc/X11/xorg.conf_backup 
sudo sed -i -e 's/"ati"/"fglrx"/' /etc/X11/xorg.conf</screen></para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
			    <para>If you are using an NForce2-based motherboard you will also need to do the following:</para>
			    <para><screen>
sudo gedit /etc/X11/xorg.conf
			    </screen></para>
			    <para>Change <quote>Section "Device"</quote> add the following line:</para>
			    <para><screen>
  Option  "UseInternalAGPGART" "no"</screen></para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
			    <para>Restart your machine for changes to take effect.</para>
			</listitem>
			</orderedlist>
		</answer>
	    </qandaentry>
	    </qandaset>
